<section xml:id="sec_mag-and-dir" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Magnitude and Direction</title>
		
<p>As you have seen, one of the most common shorthand ways of describing a vector is as something with <q>magnitude and direction</q>.  Determining or working with these two quantities are essential for using vectors in physics.</p>

	
	<exercises>
	<title>Activities</title>
	
	
		
<exercise xml:id="class_three-vectors">
        <title>Warm-up 1: Three Vectors</title>
		
		<p></p>
		
		    <p>Which of the following is <m>\vec{C}</m>?</p>
		
			<figure xml:id="fig_3Vecs">
		<title>Three Vectors Figure</title>
		 <caption>Three vectors in a triangle.</caption>
		<image source="3Vecs.png" width = "50%">
			<description></description></image>
  </figure>

  	<ol marker="A">
		<li>
			<p>
				<m>\vec{C} = \vec{A} + \vec{B}</m>
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				<m>\vec{C} = \vec{B} + \vec{A}</m>
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				<m>\vec{C} = \vec{A} - \vec{B}</m>
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				<m>\vec{C} = \vec{B} - \vec{A}</m>
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				None of the above
			</p>
		</li>
	</ol>
  
		
	</exercise>

