	<exercise xml:id="arcs_planets-building">
        <title>The Planets around the Sun</title>
		<statement>
		<p></p>
		
		    <p>
				Consider four of the planets distributed around the Sun: Earth, Mars, Jupiter, and Saturn. 
Suppose you want each planet to be able to send a message to any of the other planets.
			</p>
			<p>
				Start by choosing any two planets. 
Your objective is to find the angle at which to direct the message from one planet to the other. 
			</p>
			<p>
Begin by brainstorming what information you think would be useful to you in achieving this objective.

			</p>
			<p> Below is information about the position of each planet relative to the Sun and an arbitrary positive axis starting at the Sun.</p>

			<ul>
				<li>
					<p>
						Earth: 1 AU from the Sun; 150 degrees left of the axis
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Mars: 1.5 AU from the Sun; 90 degrees right of the axis
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Jupiter: 5.2 AU from the Sun; 120 degrees left of the axis
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Saturn: 9.5 AU from the Sun; 30 degrees right of the axis
					</p>
				</li>
			</ul>
				
	</statement>
	<hint>
		<p>
			This is a good activity to practice the steps in <xref ref="fig_calculation"/>. 
			In particular, consider how much work might be saved by solving for one pair of planets symbolically in contrast to solving for every pair of planets separately.
		</p>
	</hint>
	</exercise>




